00:29:03,031 --> 00:29:05,331
Yellow was a unifying color they both carry

509
00:29:05,331 --> 00:29:07,312
that can read from a distance.

510
00:29:07,312 --> 00:29:10,553
Since we were designing two playable characters,

511
00:29:10,553 --> 00:29:13,554
their outfits and colors had to read clearly.

512
00:29:15,068 --> 00:29:18,350
in After Party, in order to get out of hell,

513
00:29:18,350 --> 00:29:20,811
their friendship had to be put to the test.

514
00:29:20,811 --> 00:29:25,454
For Satan, so we wanted his design

515
00:29:25,454 --> 00:29:26,214
to be iconic and familiar.

516
00:29:26,214 --> 00:29:32,177
You know, he's been running hell for over a million years,

517
00:29:32,177 --> 00:29:33,918
and so Adam had this idea of layering

518
00:29:33,918 --> 00:29:37,620
fashionable clothes over time to kind of beef himself up.

519
00:29:37,620 --> 00:29:41,521
His personality is a cross between Kanye West,

520
00:29:42,457 --> 00:29:49,519
and Dr. Frankenfurter from Rocky Horror Picture Show.

521
00:29:49,519 --> 00:29:55,821
So Satan's backstory, he's the first kid in heaven

522
00:29:55,821 --> 00:29:58,221
that was put into detention.

523
00:29:58,221 --> 00:30:01,082
So in hell, he runs the party 24 hours a day,

524
00:30:01,082 --> 00:30:03,243
every day for centuries.

525
00:30:03,243 --> 00:30:04,523
His design was so crazy,

526
00:30:04,523 --> 00:30:07,044
so we were wondering how we were gonna model him

527
00:30:07,044 --> 00:30:08,465
and kind of stay in a decent poly count.

528
00:30:11,927 --> 00:30:14,288
So from concept art, it was gonna be a challenge,

529
00:30:14,288 --> 00:30:15,549
but we did it.

530
00:30:15,549 --> 00:30:17,570
Eric Romano, Claire Chen, and I tag teamed

531
00:30:17,570 --> 00:30:19,292
in how to build him correctly.

532
00:30:19,292 --> 00:30:24,115
Satan's model, I think, clocks in at around 13,000 triangles.

533
00:30:24,115 --> 00:30:27,657
So the next problem to solve was how to do the rig,

534
00:30:27,657 --> 00:30:29,739
how to animate all these characters.

535
00:30:29,739 --> 00:30:33,141
So how do we bring all these characters

536
00:30:33,141 --> 00:30:34,062
to life in After Party?

537
00:30:42,008 --> 00:30:45,170
They had to have cool outfits, strong design shape,

538
00:30:45,170 --> 00:30:48,831
posture and animation that caters to their personality type.

539
00:30:48,831 --> 00:30:52,633
So for rigging, we use Anzuvin's setup machine for games,

540
00:30:52,633 --> 00:30:57,375
the super cool, easy rigging tool that bakes animations

541
00:30:57,375 --> 00:30:59,216
and exports FBX files.

542
00:30:59,216 --> 00:31:04,098
So in Maya, we also use a plugin called Studio Library

543
00:31:04,098 --> 00:31:06,799
where you can save, transfer animations and poses.

544
00:31:09,623 --> 00:31:12,225
We were also able to use blend shapes

545
00:31:12,225 --> 00:31:15,007
for human faces and demon masks.

546
00:31:15,007 --> 00:31:17,848
We were able to transfer all the blend shape items

547
00:31:17,848 --> 00:31:20,870
across each mask type.

548
00:31:20,870 --> 00:31:27,314
Their personalities, Lola is protective,

549
00:31:27,314 --> 00:31:30,495
snarky, and independent.

550
00:31:30,495 --> 00:31:33,337
Milo is friendly, nervous, and a square.

551
00:31:34,895 --> 00:31:40,119
The animation had to communicate emotions and personality clearly

552
00:31:40,119 --> 00:31:42,961
for the acting to read from a distance.

553
00:31:42,961 --> 00:31:47,845
They had to be comedic, alive, and have a lot of heart.

554
00:31:47,845 --> 00:31:52,749
So Satan was a huge, complicated character

555
00:31:52,749 --> 00:31:54,330
with layers of clothing and props.

556
00:31:54,330 --> 00:31:57,813
It was just a big challenge for his rig to work properly.

557
00:31:58,512 --> 00:32:01,974
So I started to experiment with cloth component in Unity.

558
00:32:01,974 --> 00:32:05,116
I kind of just started off with a simple banner flag,

559
00:32:05,116 --> 00:32:07,778
kind of figure out how it works in Unity.

560
00:32:07,778 --> 00:32:10,720
So now we added cloth dynamics and digital,

561
00:32:10,720 --> 00:32:14,962
just rigid bodies to help our characters feel alive

562
00:32:14,962 --> 00:32:16,724
and to get that free overlap

563
00:32:16,724 --> 00:32:21,787
and follow through in the animation.

564
00:32:21,787 --> 00:32:25,749
So I had to group all and combine all the right pieces

565
00:32:25,749 --> 00:32:27,610
to reduce the amount of draw calls we have.

566
00:32:29,792 --> 00:32:32,295
So we have his feathers were cloth,

567
00:32:32,295 --> 00:32:35,478
his necklace and the skulls around his neck

568
00:32:35,478 --> 00:32:37,960
are all rigid bodies.

569
00:32:37,960 --> 00:32:42,004
We also added colliders so the colliders would push

570
00:32:42,004 --> 00:32:45,727
and prevent penetration of the cloth around it.

571
00:32:45,727 --> 00:32:48,830
The materials and shaders was another obstacle

572
00:32:48,830 --> 00:32:50,471
to cross with our characters.

573
00:32:50,471 --> 00:32:53,394
So how do we render them similar to our concept art

574
00:32:53,394 --> 00:32:55,316
so they feel part of the game environment?

575
00:33:01,049 --> 00:33:03,271
Their textures had to come through in the models

576
00:33:03,271 --> 00:33:07,114
as well as seamlessly fit into the new environment,

577
00:33:07,114 --> 00:33:08,435
modeling and lighting.

578
00:33:08,435 --> 00:33:10,937
They look great with just an ambient occlusion

579
00:33:10,937 --> 00:33:13,579
GI style rendering with a simple background

580
00:33:13,579 --> 00:33:16,341
with standard Unity shader,

581
00:33:16,341 --> 00:33:17,922
but it just was not working at all

582
00:33:17,922 --> 00:33:23,166
or seeing them clearly with our busy environment scenes.

583
00:33:23,166 --> 00:33:27,249
So our lead engineer, Bryant,

584
00:33:27,249 --> 00:33:29,291
had to create a custom toon shader

585
00:33:29,291 --> 00:33:30,392
for the characters as well.

586
00:33:31,357 --> 00:33:32,698
we called it Bar Toon Shader.

587
00:33:32,698 --> 00:33:35,119
It consisted of three layers.

588
00:33:35,119 --> 00:33:38,422
So we wanted the lights to have a bright, saturated colors,

589
00:33:38,422 --> 00:33:41,725
but that washes out all the bright, varied colors

590
00:33:41,725 --> 00:33:45,447
we put into the characters' textures.

591
00:33:45,447 --> 00:33:47,729
We needed a custom shader to keep all the local colors

592
00:33:47,729 --> 00:33:49,791
consistent through each lighting situation.

593
00:33:49,791 --> 00:33:55,055
So the Bar Toon Shader, it has base lighting,

594
00:33:55,055 --> 00:33:57,917
which calculates the global illumination input

595
00:33:57,917 --> 00:33:58,958
from the light probes.

596
00:33:59,932 --> 00:34:03,474
A standard toon shader that desaturates the light source

597
00:34:03,474 --> 00:34:06,476
so the local colors pop even though

598
00:34:06,476 --> 00:34:08,938
the light source is saturated.

599
00:34:08,938 --> 00:34:12,180
The harsh rim light picks up any colored lights

600
00:34:12,180 --> 00:34:13,681
on the edges of the character.

601
00:34:13,681 --> 00:34:20,785
So the top GIF uses the standard shader

602
00:34:20,785 --> 00:34:23,407
and the bottom GIF uses the bar toon shader.

603
00:34:23,407 --> 00:34:26,729
Now you can clearly see that our characters

604
00:34:26,729 --> 00:34:29,090
as they cross that dumpster fire light source.

605
00:34:30,494 --> 00:34:38,146
You can see the local color as well as seeing that rim wrap lighting around the edges.

606
00:34:38,146 --> 00:34:43,655
Lighting, we also want it to look like the illustration, so how do we render volumetric

607
00:34:43,655 --> 00:34:45,398
lighting with a ton of characters?

608
00:34:50,045 --> 00:34:52,586
The engineers and designers were swamped,

609
00:34:52,586 --> 00:34:55,388
so we picked up an HX volumetric lighting

610
00:34:55,388 --> 00:34:56,529
from the Unity store.

611
00:34:56,529 --> 00:35:02,112
But later on, our engineers rewrote the shaders

612
00:35:02,112 --> 00:35:05,795
and lighting, and made a fake volumetric light

613
00:35:05,795 --> 00:35:10,037
for each character, so it kind of saves us

614
00:35:10,037 --> 00:35:14,740
on just any Unity caching.

615
00:35:15,787 --> 00:35:18,449
We had one directional light that's a shadow caster,

616
00:35:18,449 --> 00:35:20,750
the rest were point lights, they were just light probes

617
00:35:20,750 --> 00:35:23,612
that were baked into the environment.

618
00:35:23,612 --> 00:35:30,677
So I designed one of the characters named Sister Mary Wormhorn,

619
00:35:30,677 --> 00:35:33,098
Milo and Lola's personal demon.

620
00:35:33,098 --> 00:35:35,520
In hell, you just don't get tortured physically,

621
00:35:35,520 --> 00:35:37,621
you also get tortured mentally by creatures

622
00:35:37,621 --> 00:35:39,803
birthed from your subconscious fears.

623
00:35:41,387 --> 00:35:49,990
Blend shapes on the arms were also there to kind of create that nice noodly shape.

624
00:35:49,990 --> 00:35:53,871
We also added a mission layer to the bar to shader to help with glowing mask

625
00:35:53,871 --> 00:35:57,832
and other props like Christmas lights and lampshades.

626
00:35:57,832 --> 00:36:02,214
With animation, we wanted to push the timing, acting, and hilarity.

627
00:36:02,214 --> 00:36:07,195
Here's one of our party demons, Asmodeus, doing the running man.

628
00:36:13,630 --> 00:36:15,610
Now let's look at both environment and characters

629
00:36:15,610 --> 00:36:19,312
working well together at our vertical slice first in IZARD.

630
00:36:19,312 --> 00:36:22,493
The bartender shader and the bartoon shader in action.

631
00:36:22,493 --> 00:36:38,680
With one of our three little words being alive,

632
00:36:38,680 --> 00:36:41,421
how do we design all the NPC crowd characters?

633
00:36:46,381 --> 00:36:52,006
We had the idea of demons wearing masks and glowing eyes to visually represent them and tie them to this world.

634
00:36:52,006 --> 00:36:57,670
We also played with different proportions to vary their beltline or hip height.

635
00:36:57,670 --> 00:37:03,635
We also gave them unifying skin color but grounded them by adding clothing.

636
00:37:03,635 --> 00:37:08,599
In contrast, humans have dot eyes and have a variety of skin tones and outfits.

637
00:37:13,195 --> 00:37:26,340
We created a variation of horns and mask types for demons.

638
00:37:26,340 --> 00:37:27,941
We referenced a lot of different outfits

639
00:37:27,941 --> 00:37:34,283
that span across different times and cultures.

640
00:37:34,283 --> 00:37:35,964
We were able to scale out each rig type

641
00:37:35,964 --> 00:37:38,725
by having a variation of hair props and texture swaps

642
00:37:38,725 --> 00:37:41,706
as well as changing your body mass with blend shapes.

643
00:37:42,888 --> 00:37:46,549
Later on, we started to give them cause of death props

644
00:37:46,549 --> 00:37:49,770
for just interesting gags.

645
00:37:49,770 --> 00:37:51,710
So another challenge was managing the crowd

646
00:37:51,710 --> 00:37:55,131
in NPC characters.

647
00:37:55,131 --> 00:37:56,812
How do we make our environments look alive?

648
00:37:56,812 --> 00:38:01,493
Aaron Cheney, one of our engineers,

649
00:38:01,493 --> 00:38:02,953
created a dynamic crowd system.

650
00:38:09,747 --> 00:38:12,008
So the dynamic crowd system leveraged control,

651
00:38:12,008 --> 00:38:15,051
randomness to populate hell in an automated,

652
00:38:15,051 --> 00:38:17,353
naturalistic way while staying out of the player's way.

653
00:38:17,353 --> 00:38:21,796
With our dynamic crowd system,

654
00:38:21,796 --> 00:38:24,518
we also wanted to avoid characters walking

655
00:38:24,518 --> 00:38:26,040
and standing in front of the camera view.

656
00:38:26,040 --> 00:38:29,823
It's comedic, but we needed more control

657
00:38:29,823 --> 00:38:31,584
when staging these AI characters.

658
00:38:36,382 --> 00:38:38,323
So basically we had to Marie Kondo some scenes.

659
00:38:38,323 --> 00:38:41,064
We had a combination of dynamic crowds

660
00:38:41,064 --> 00:38:42,645
and static characters that sparked joy.

661
00:38:42,645 --> 00:38:47,187
I created some rule sets for our game designers to follow

662
00:38:47,187 --> 00:38:50,309
and keep in mind when looking and hooking up scenes.

663
00:38:50,309 --> 00:38:52,890
Now that all the assets are made,

664
00:38:52,890 --> 00:38:57,073
it was critical to have the animations acting in staging

665
00:38:57,073 --> 00:38:58,013
to have a convincing performance.

666
00:38:58,013 --> 00:38:59,554
For eye tracing,

667
00:39:05,066 --> 00:39:07,787
We wanted the crowds to react to our player characters.

668
00:39:07,787 --> 00:39:10,409
If our characters toast or cheers,

669
00:39:10,409 --> 00:39:12,970
demons and humans in certain proximity

670
00:39:12,970 --> 00:39:14,471
will also start to cheers with you.

671
00:39:14,471 --> 00:39:17,012
So similar to Oxenfree,

672
00:39:17,012 --> 00:39:19,854
we never try to take player control away,

673
00:39:19,854 --> 00:39:26,137
like an in-game cutscene would do.

674
00:39:26,137 --> 00:39:28,438
Crowd placement have a purpose and story

675
00:39:28,438 --> 00:39:29,739
to really sell the world of Hell.

676
00:39:30,860 --> 00:39:34,204
For example, the scene was posed

677
00:39:34,204 --> 00:39:36,706
with barbecuing demons on the left,

678
00:39:36,706 --> 00:39:38,928
and ultimately you would have NPCs standing in line

679
00:39:38,928 --> 00:39:39,549
for hell tacos.

680
00:39:39,549 --> 00:39:44,033
On the far right, you have a drunk demon throwing up,

681
00:39:44,033 --> 00:39:46,636
and another picking a pick and tweeting it about

682
00:39:46,636 --> 00:39:49,038
and posting it on Bicker.

683
00:39:49,038 --> 00:39:51,240
Bicker is our version of Twitter in the game.

684
00:39:56,360 --> 00:39:59,741
We also created a consistent camera guide

685
00:39:59,741 --> 00:40:01,221
to manage height, distance of our camera

686
00:40:01,221 --> 00:40:03,341
to our player characters.

687
00:40:03,341 --> 00:40:08,443
The game of beer pong and PC characters

688
00:40:08,443 --> 00:40:10,683
pay attention to the main characters

689
00:40:10,683 --> 00:40:13,964
as well as to react to who's winning or losing.

690
00:40:13,964 --> 00:40:17,425
In After Party, you can drink, trash talk,

691
00:40:17,425 --> 00:40:19,365
and play beer pong all at the same time.

692
00:40:27,983 --> 00:40:30,264
Here's where staging our player characters,

693
00:40:30,264 --> 00:40:32,145
dynamic crowd system, static characters,

694
00:40:32,145 --> 00:40:43,049
environment playing a role in making the scene work.

695
00:40:43,049 --> 00:40:44,610
My job as art director is to keep track

696
00:40:44,610 --> 00:40:46,210
of each thing that we build and design.

697
00:40:46,210 --> 00:40:49,732
I really follow it through from the beginning

698
00:40:49,732 --> 00:40:50,712
to the end of production.

699
00:41:01,189 --> 00:41:03,691
So art style, by finding creative workflows

700
00:41:03,691 --> 00:41:06,034
and bringing concept artists more into the production,

701
00:41:06,034 --> 00:41:07,795
it really helped bridge the gap

702
00:41:07,795 --> 00:41:09,176
in concept art and in-game art.

703
00:41:09,176 --> 00:41:11,599
We were able to solve our art problem

704
00:41:11,599 --> 00:41:14,181
by bringing all the engineers and designers together.

705
00:41:14,181 --> 00:41:15,802
Technique, have super smart engineers and designers.

706
00:41:26,273 --> 00:41:28,234
to have them on your side, that they understand

707
00:41:28,234 --> 00:41:31,756
shader work, dynamic card systems, game design limitations

708
00:41:31,756 --> 00:41:33,898
that helped us create the game successfully.

709
00:41:33,898 --> 00:41:37,380
Bringing them into the fold and explaining

710
00:41:37,380 --> 00:41:38,921
the technical problems helped bridge the gap

711
00:41:38,921 --> 00:41:40,722
between concept art and game art.

712
00:41:40,722 --> 00:41:46,125
Scope, create a game that fits your budget and timeline.

713
00:41:46,125 --> 00:41:49,888
Always weigh the risk of adding too many features.

714
00:41:49,888 --> 00:41:53,410
We were ambitious in making a bigger game than Oxenfree,

715
00:41:53,410 --> 00:41:54,110
but we succeeded.

716
00:41:55,925 --> 00:41:58,886
It took a while to get there, but we definitely

717
00:41:58,886 --> 00:42:01,567
overscoped a tiny bit on this game.

718
00:42:01,567 --> 00:42:05,428
Skill set and team size.

719
00:42:05,428 --> 00:42:09,029
Lean on your team's strengths to empower, challenge,

720
00:42:09,029 --> 00:42:10,769
and nurture a positive working environment.

721
00:42:10,769 --> 00:42:13,610
Artists learning from each other,

722
00:42:13,610 --> 00:42:17,011
scale the team to the proper scope of the project.

723
00:42:17,011 --> 00:42:18,631
With our concept artists working in production,

724
00:42:18,631 --> 00:42:20,652
they were able to have more footprint in the game.

725
00:42:23,998 --> 00:42:26,799
Keep it small and simple.

726
00:42:26,799 --> 00:42:29,700
Make a simple game with a few mechanics.

727
00:42:29,700 --> 00:42:32,942
Prototype them early and make sure

728
00:42:32,942 --> 00:42:35,383
they hit all your design pillars.

729
00:42:35,383 --> 00:42:38,384
I think starting with a small vertical slice

730
00:42:38,384 --> 00:42:40,465
would have helped us spot troubled waters very early.

731
00:42:40,465 --> 00:42:43,806
Failure, don't be afraid to fail.

732
00:42:43,806 --> 00:42:45,747
Failure is part of success.

733
00:42:45,747 --> 00:42:48,228
We were honest and supported each other

734
00:42:48,228 --> 00:42:49,269
in finding solutions.

735
00:42:49,269 --> 00:42:52,090
So there were no egos at all in pointing fingers

736
00:42:52,090 --> 00:42:52,990
in who made a mistake.

737
00:42:53,243 --> 00:42:56,746
we banded together as a team to find a solution

738
00:42:56,746 --> 00:42:58,568
in creating the new technique and pipeline.

739
00:42:58,568 --> 00:42:59,588
Collaborate and communicate.

740
00:42:59,588 --> 00:43:05,633
Don't be afraid to raise a red flag when problems arise.

741
00:43:05,633 --> 00:43:10,817
Be open to learn from each other as team members.

742
00:43:10,817 --> 00:43:12,939
Together, find creative ways to solve that problem.

743
00:43:12,939 --> 00:43:16,001
You know, don't be married to anything that you create.

744
00:43:16,001 --> 00:43:18,823
Be open to change and things being cut.

745
00:43:18,823 --> 00:43:20,524
Old monitors were just too precious

746
00:43:20,524 --> 00:43:22,546
and we weren't able to use any of them.

747
00:43:25,518 --> 00:43:27,580
Focus, with the three little words,

748
00:43:27,580 --> 00:43:28,941
it helped us check ourselves when it came to

749
00:43:28,941 --> 00:43:30,062
exchanges about tone, art, and design.

750
00:43:30,062 --> 00:43:31,464
It kept us on the right track.

751
00:43:31,464 --> 00:43:34,107
Do you guys remember the three little words?

752
00:43:34,107 --> 00:43:39,252
We were able to succeed in creating a world

753
00:43:39,252 --> 00:43:40,853
that feels comedic.

754
00:43:57,976 --> 00:44:00,798
I know Brian Cannon, our legionnaire, is probably freaking out right now because of all the

755
00:44:00,798 --> 00:44:03,220
draw calls in the game, but the game has to look alive, even though dead in hell.

756
00:44:03,220 --> 00:44:04,821
A story of friendship that lasts through time.

757
00:44:04,821 --> 00:44:07,983
Seriously though, at Knight School, we try to create sincere stories.

758
00:44:26,410 --> 00:44:28,692
and create characters everyone resonates with.

759
00:44:28,692 --> 00:44:29,412
So, sincerely yours, Ruel.

760
00:44:29,412 --> 00:44:30,653
Thank you GDC.

